# Cloud Computing Lab - Program 4
## Program 4: Create a New User from Root Using Identity and Access Management (IAM)

## Step 1: Login as Root User

1. Open AWS Management Console.
2. Login using the AWS root account.

Root user has full access to all AWS services, IAM permissions, billing, and account-level settings.

For this program, root user is used to create and manage IAM users and permissions.

---

## Step 2: Open IAM Dashboard

1. In the AWS search bar, search:
IAM
Open IAM Dashboard.
In the left-side menu, click:
Users
Step 3: Create New IAM User
Click:
Create user
Enter user name:
test-user
Click:
Next
In permissions options, choose:
Attach policies directly

For first demonstration, do not attach S3 permission yet.

Click:
Next
Review the user details.
Click:
Create user

The IAM user test-user is now created.

Step 4: Note the IAM User ARN
Open the created user:
test-user
Copy or note the IAM user ARN.

It will look similar to:

arn:aws:iam::ACCOUNT-ID:user/test-user

ARN stands for Amazon Resource Name. It uniquely identifies AWS resources.

Step 5: Enable Console Access for IAM User
Open:
IAM → Users → test-user
Go to:
Security credentials
Find:
Console access
Click:
Enable console access
Select:
IAM user
Enable console access.
Choose:
Custom password
Enter password:
TestUser@123
For quick lab execution, untick:
User must create a new password at next sign-in
Click:
Apply

After this, copy the following details:

Console sign-in URL
Username
Password

Example:

Console URL: https://ACCOUNT-ID.signin.aws.amazon.com/console
Username: test-user
Password: TestUser@123

Do not upload real passwords or access keys to GitHub.

Step 6: Login as IAM User
Open a new browser tab or incognito window.
Paste the IAM user console sign-in URL.
Enter:
Username: test-user
Password: TestUser@123
Click:
Sign in

The IAM user will now login to AWS Console.

Step 7: Try to Access S3 Without Permission
After logging in as IAM user, search:
S3
Open Amazon S3.

Since no S3 permission has been assigned yet, the user may get an error like:

Access Denied
You do not have permission to access this resource.

This shows that a newly created IAM user does not automatically get access to AWS services.

Create and Attach S3 Policy
Step 8: Login Back as Root User
Go back to the root user browser tab.
Search:
IAM
Open IAM Dashboard.
Step 9: Create IAM Policy for S3 Access
In IAM Dashboard, click:
Policies
Click:
Create policy
Select:
JSON
Delete the existing JSON and paste the following policy:
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "S3FullAccessForLab",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": "s3:*",
      "Resource": "*"
    }
  ]
}

This policy allows full access to Amazon S3 for lab demonstration.

Click:
Next
Enter policy name:
PG04-S3-Access-Policy
Enter description:
Allows S3 access for IAM user in cloud computing lab
Click:
Create policy
Step 10: Attach Policy to IAM User
Go to:
IAM → Users
Open:
test-user
Go to:
Permissions
Click:
Add permissions
Choose:
Attach policies directly
Search for:
PG04-S3-Access-Policy
Select the policy.
Click:
Next
Click:
Add permissions

Now the IAM user has S3 access.

Step 11: Login Again as IAM User
Go back to the IAM user browser tab.
Logout and login again, or refresh the page.
Login using:
Username: test-user
Password: TestUser@123
Step 12: Access S3 as IAM User
Search:
S3
Open Amazon S3.

Now the IAM user should be able to access S3 successfully.

This proves that permission attached through IAM policy is working.

Step 13: Create S3 Bucket as IAM User
In Amazon S3, click:
Create bucket
Enter a globally unique bucket name:
musaib-pg04-iam-demo-20260701

Use your own unique bucket name if this name is already taken.

Select region:
Asia Pacific Mumbai / ap-south-1
Keep other settings as default.
Click:
Create bucket

If the bucket is created successfully, the IAM user has correct S3 permission.

Optional: Create IAM Group and Add User
Step 14: Create IAM User Group

Login as root user.

Go to:

IAM → User groups

Click:

Create group

Enter group name:

S3-Users-Group

Click:

Create group

IAM groups are used to organize users and assign permissions to multiple users together.

Step 15: Attach Policy to Group
Open:
S3-Users-Group
Go to:
Permissions
Click:
Add permissions
Select:
Attach policies
Search:
PG04-S3-Access-Policy
Select the policy.
Click:
Add permissions

Now the group has S3 permission.

Step 16: Add IAM User to Group
Open:
IAM → User groups → S3-Users-Group
Click:
Add users
Select:
test-user
Click:
Add users

Now test-user receives permissions through the group also.

Optional: Remove or Delete Policy from IAM User
Step 17: Remove Direct Policy from User

If permission needs to be removed:

Go to:
IAM → Users → test-user
Open:
Permissions
Select the attached policy:
PG04-S3-Access-Policy
Click:
Remove
